Homework 3: Data wrangling

Use the FiveThirtyEight elections data to answer the following questions about the 2024 election results.

library(tidyverse)
presidential_elections<-read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/fivethirtyeight/election-results/main/election_results_presidential.csv")
presidential_elections<-presidential_elections|>
  # only 2024 general election
  filter(cycle==2024, stage=="general")|>
  # removing separate congressional district data for 2 states
  filter(!str_detect(state, "CD-"))|>
  # fixing party IDs (NY had Harris/Trump as DFL in some precincts)
  mutate(party = case_when(candidate_name == "Kamala Harris" ~ "DEM",
                           candidate_name == "Donald Trump" ~ "REP",
                           .default = party
                           ))

Question 1.

Create a data set with the two party vote share and the winning candidate for each state (plus D.C.) in the 2024 presidential election. Your results should have 51 rows, with a separate column for Democratic and Republican vote share, and a column for the name of the winner in that state.

Question 1. Answer

Weâll need to filter out Puerto Rico (although I wonât count off for this) as well as drop any candidates who werenât on the Democratic or Republican ballots. Then, we can group by state/party/candidate to calculate the total vote for each candidate in each state, and finally weâll group by state and calculate state wide two-party vote and vote share.

This will give us the data in long format - with two rows for each state (one for Trump and one for Harris)

# Code here

presidential_voteshares<-presidential_elections|>
  filter(state !='Puerto Rico')|>
  filter(party %in% c("DEM", "REP"))|>
  group_by(party, state, candidate_name)|>
  summarise(votes = sum(votes))|>
  group_by(state)|>
  mutate(total_votes = sum(votes),
         voteshare = votes/total_votes,
         winner = candidate_name[which.max(voteshare)]
            )|>
  ungroup()


presidential_voteshares|>
  slice_head(n=5)
party state candidate_name votes total_votes voteshare winner
DEM Alabama Kamala Harris 772412 2235028 0.3455939 Donald Trump
DEM Alaska Kamala Harris 140026 324484 0.4315344 Donald Trump
DEM Arizona Kamala Harris 1582860 3353102 0.4720584 Donald Trump
DEM Arkansas Kamala Harris 396905 1156146 0.3433001 Donald Trump
DEM California Kamala Harris 9276179 15357876 0.6040014 Kamala Harris

Now we just need to convert this to wide format:

voteshares_wide<-presidential_voteshares|>
  select(state, voteshare, party, total_votes, winner)|>
  pivot_wider(names_from = party, values_from =voteshare)
  
  

voteshares_wide|>
  slice_head(n=5)

Question 2.

Use the data on 2024 senate races to identify the senate candidates who most out-performed the presidential candidate for their respective parties.

In other words: if the senate candidate was a Democrat, compare their share of the two-party vote to Harris vote share in that state, if theyâre a Republican, compare their share to the statewide vote share for Harris (Iâll leave it up to you to determine how to handle Bernie Sandersâ¦).

Question 2. Answer

Step one is to just calculate each candidates share of the two party vote. The approach here should be very similar to what we did in question 1, except that weâll want to use the ballot_party variable, set Bernie Sanders and Angus King as Democrats, and group by race_id in addition to grouping by state (this captures the cases like California where there was more than one seat up for election)

For our join, its probably easier if we just leave everything in long format:

senate_voteshares<-read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/fivethirtyeight/election-results/refs/heads/main/election_results_senate.csv')|>
  filter(cycle==2024,
         stage == "general"
         
         )|>
  mutate(ballot_party = case_when(candidate_name == "Bernie Sanders" ~ "DEM",
                                  .default = ballot_party
                                  ))|>
  filter(state !='Puerto Rico')|>
  filter(ballot_party %in% c("DEM", "REP"))|>
  group_by(ballot_party, state, candidate_name, race_id)|>
  summarise(votes = sum(votes))|>
  group_by(state, race_id)|>
  mutate(total_votes = sum(votes),
         voteshare = votes/total_votes)|>
  ungroup()|>
  rename(senator=candidate_name)|>
  arrange(state, race_id)

senate_voteshares|>
  slice_head(n=5)
ballot_party state senator race_id votes total_votes voteshare
DEM Arizona Ruben Gallego 9505 1676335 3272096 0.5123123
REP Arizona Kari Lake 9505 1595761 3272096 0.4876877
DEM California Adam B. Schiff 9506 9036252 15348846 0.5887252
REP California Steve Garvey 9506 6312594 15348846 0.4112748
DEM California Adam B. Schiff 10013 8837051 15041688 0.5875039

Then, weâll want to use a join to combine the tables based on party and state:

combined_races<-left_join(presidential_voteshares, senate_voteshares, 
                          by=join_by(party == ballot_party, state==state), 
                          suffix=c('_pres', '_senate'))

combined_races|>
  slice_head(n=5)
party state candidate_name votes_pres total_votes_pres voteshare_pres winner senator race_id votes_senate total_votes_senate voteshare_senate
DEM Alabama Kamala Harris 772412 2235028 0.3455939 Donald Trump NA NA NA NA NA
DEM Alaska Kamala Harris 140026 324484 0.4315344 Donald Trump NA NA NA NA NA
DEM Arizona Kamala Harris 1582860 3353102 0.4720584 Donald Trump Ruben Gallego 9505 1676335 3272096 0.5123123
DEM Arkansas Kamala Harris 396905 1156146 0.3433001 Donald Trump NA NA NA NA NA
DEM California Kamala Harris 9276179 15357876 0.6040014 Kamala Harris Adam B. Schiff 9506 9036252 15348846 0.5887252

Finally, weâll want to calculate the difference in senate vote share compared to presidential vote share

voteshare_diff<-combined_races|>
  mutate(difference = voteshare_senate-voteshare_pres)|>
  select(party, state, senator, voteshare_senate, voteshare_pres, difference)|>
  arrange(-difference)

voteshare_diff|>
  slice_head(n=5)
party state senator voteshare_senate voteshare_pres difference
REP Maine Demi Kouzounas 0.7618325 0.4645569 0.2972756
REP Maryland Larry Hogan 0.4394674 0.3524524 0.0870150
DEM Nebraska Dan Osborn 0.4665296 0.3957966 0.0707330
DEM Montana Jon Tester 0.4636091 0.3971095 0.0664996
DEM Minnesota Amy Klobuchar 0.5811777 0.5217170 0.0594607

This kind of data might be easier to understand with a visualization. Hereâs an example of using a scatter plot to interpret the results, along with some additional code to add a candidate label to each point and a 45 degree reference line to distinguish underperformers from overperformers.

Note that Demi Kouzanas and David Costello probably indicate cases that we would want to handle separately: theyâre both from Maine and they technically ran in a three-way race against the incumbent Angus King.

library(ggrepel)

voteshare_diff|>
  mutate(senator = paste0(senator,", ", state))|>
  ggplot(aes(x=voteshare_pres, y=voteshare_senate, color=party, label=senator)) +
  geom_abline(intercept=0, slope=1, lty=2, col='black') +
  geom_text_repel() +
  geom_point()+
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Senate vs. Presidential Share of two-party vote in the 2024 election",
       x ='Presidential two party vote % in state',
       y ='Senate two party vote % in state'
    ) +
  ylim(c(0, 1)) +
  xlim(c(0, 1)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("blue", "red")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent)

Question 3.

Create a new data set where each row contains a dummy variable to indicate whether both countries are democratic, one country is democratic, or both countries are non-democratic. Then use summarize and group_by to calculate the percentage of democratic, mixed and non-democratic dyads that have experienced a civil war.

# data on democracy
regimes<-read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Neilblund/GVPT628Fall2025/refs/heads/main/Data/democracy_data.csv')

# data on war dyads
dyadic_wars<-read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Neilblund/GVPT628Fall2025/refs/heads/main/Data/war_data.csv')

Question 3. Answer

Weâll need to use two left joins to get the democracy levels for both members of each dyad:

# code here

data<-
  dyadic_wars|>
  left_join(regimes, by=join_by(country_1_id == country_id))|>
  left_join(regimes, by=join_by(country_2_id == country_id))

data|>
  slice_head(n=5)
country_1_name country_1_id country_2_name country_2_id any_wars country_name.x regime.x country_name.y regime.y
United States 2 Canada 20 No United States Democracy Canada Democracy
United States 2 Cuba 40 No United States Democracy Cuba Non-Democracy
United States 2 Haiti 41 No United States Democracy Haiti Non-Democracy
United States 2 Dominican Republic 42 No United States Democracy Dominican Republic Non-Democracy
United States 2 Jamaica 51 No United States Democracy Jamaica Democracy

And then create a dyadic regime type indicator and use group_by with summarize to get the proportion of wars in each category:

data<-data|>
  mutate(dyadic_regime = case_when(
    regime.x == "Democracy" & regime.y == "Democracy" ~ "Both Democratic",
    regime.x == "Non-Democracy" & regime.y == "Non-Democracy" ~ "Neither Democratic",
    regime.x == "Non-Democracy" | regime.y == "Non-Democracy" ~ "Mixed"

    ))



aggregate_data<-data|>
  group_by(dyadic_regime, any_wars)|>
  summarize(n = n ())|>
  drop_na()|>
  group_by(dyadic_regime)|>
  mutate(proportion  = n/sum(n))

aggregate_data
dyadic_regime any_wars n proportion
Both Democratic No 666 1.0000000
Mixed No 3826 0.9968734
Mixed Yes 12 0.0031266
Neither Democratic No 5042 0.9984158
Neither Democratic Yes 8 0.0015842

Finally, for the sake of readability, we might want to use a pivot and values_fill to get a wide format table:

aggregate_data|>
  select(-n)|>
  pivot_wider(names_from  = any_wars, values_from = proportion, values_fill=0)
dyadic_regime No Yes
Both Democratic 1.0000000 0.0000000
Mixed 0.9968734 0.0031266
Neither Democratic 0.9984158 0.0015842

Note that the overall relationship here is broadly consistent with the expectations of the dyadic peace, but the number of wars is so small that it would be hard to rule out random chance as an explanation for the observed result. In practice, most analyses of the democratic peace theory use militarized interstate disputes (which include violent conflicts short of war) instead of wars alone.
